segments.text: tape ran out, we were struggling with the problem of why Rockdale's lignite mine situation was apparently more progressive than a company town situation like Pullman.
Well, you know, a whole lot of that I think can be attributed to the class of businessmen and civic leaders that Rockdale had.
People like H.C. Meyer and E.B.
Phillips and

Bruce Denton, N.M. Bullock, and my father, the newspaper man, John Esten Cook, and they thought a lot of Rockdale, and they looked upon the mines out there, they were proud of the mines out there, but the
The Mexicans that worked out there in the mines had their own little community, and they kind of took care of their own affairs and celebrated this thing called the mail.
And they didn't bother anybody, and we didn't bother them.
I think it was more of a peaceful coexistence.
Right.
I've been amazed.
No one particularly thought about them being outsiders out there working, you know.
I've been amazed at the lack of labor troubles out there.
They weren't labor troubles, but labor troubles came along.
Years later after everybody got educated by the union.
They weren't labor troubles and there wasn't ethnic
There wasn't so much thought given to ethnic groups and problems that might arise from them.
They were just looked upon as part of the community.

Do you think that just the physical nature of Word of Mind were kind of... That bound to have had a whole lot to do with it, because they were, you know, out there anywhere five, six, seven miles from the center of town.
And they just sort of appeared like the farmers coming in on one case.
Right.
To the rest of the people around me.
That's right.
Well, again, I want to thank you, and I hope you didn't.
I think on some of those, on some of those Mexican celebrations, I, you know, I don't remember them because that was, I was too young to participate in that sort of thing then.
But I think there were a lot of Rockdale people that used to like to go out there.
and participate in some of them, make them celebrations.
You know, welcome them and help them celebrate.
There just wasn't that much of a mention in the paper about that.
Probably not.
And another thing you might keep in mind is newspapers in those days were a pretty far cry from newspapers today.
Oh, yes.
And the...
That wasn't the big news stories in those days.
The big news stories were strictly local and Mr. and Mrs. John Henry visiting somebody else and all of that sort of thing.
So-and-so bought such and such piece of land.
And even advertising was different in those days.
Mostly, most good civic-minded businessmen thought they should advertise
to support the paper because the town needed the paper.
And today, they advertise to get business, and I don't think that was so much the case then.
It was goodwill advertising in those days, you know.
Well, I did notice a big jump after 1936 in the number of advertisements in the paper.
I don't know if that was due to your solicitations or not, but it was just amazing to me.
There was a jump.
Well, I think you'll find that true all over the state.
Weekly newspapers have changed a lot and have become more news-conscious and more advertising-conscious, and businessmen have done the same thing.
Well, again, thank you, and I appreciate it very much.
You're sure welcome.
Good luck to you.
